Second trimester only","First and third trimesters only","Second and third trimesters only","First, second and third trimesters"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cardiovascular changes of pregnancy begin early in the \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst trimester\u003C/strong\u003E and continue throughout the \u003Cstrong\u003Esecond\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird trimesters\u003C/strong\u003E. These adaptations include increased cardiac chamber distensibility, enhanced sympathetic activity, and enlargement of all four cardiac chambers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes are necessary to accommodate:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased blood volume (30-50% increase)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased cardiac output (30-50% increase)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased oxygen demand\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEnhanced tissue perfusion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe progressive nature of these changes throughout pregnancy helps maintain adequate circulation to meet the growing metabolic demands of both mother and fetus. These adaptations begin as early as 5-8 weeks gestation and persist until delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiac changes in pregnancy include increased chamber size, enhanced contractility, and increased cardiac output throughout all trimesters.","Cardiovascular adaptations begin early in pregnancy and persist until delivery to accommodate increased metabolic demands."],"references":["Soma-Pillay P, Nelson-Piercy C, Tolppanen H, Mebazaa A. Physiological changes in pregnancy. Cardiovasc J Afr. 2016 Mar-Apr;27(2):89-94. doi: 10.5830/CVJA-2016-021. PMID: 27213856; PMCID: PMC4928162","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynec